Ordered carry out for pickup. Appreciate being able to pickup outside, but considering Covid, was not thrilled with big tubs of self-serve sauce containers. Speaking of sauce, we ordered the large container, but it was missing. Luckily, we grabbed a few of the small (and only 1/2 full) containers outside, to try some others. But that didn’t make the best option. Ok, the food: got a sampler, first time here. Rib tips were the only great thing. Cooked properly. Brisket - good, nothing special, tho. The rib bones were the worst - too much spice rub, dry *and* mushy texture - being overcooked. The ‘burnt ends’ were neither burned nor what I think of as ends. Just a large piece of brisket that was cut into chunks, but not re-smoked, or anything. At least nit drowned in sauce, as I’ve experienced elsewhere. Had Mac and cheese, very picky here, but it was great! Except so salty, almost inedible. Otherwise, great unique flavor and creamy. Potato salad unmemorable, not my favorite style, too-big potato pieces.  The seasoned fries were so salty, had to try to remove as much as possible, then ok. Over salting is clearly an issue here, pretty much across the board. We were disappointed, after reading great reviews. Would we go back? Bbq is such a personal matter that it’s hard to rate really. Some like the dry rub style, others prefer it drenched in sauce. And the sauce, again, is really a personal predilection. But regardless of how you like your rub or sauce, slow smoked bbq should always, no matter what, be tender, falling off the bone tender, wilts as soon as you take a glance at it tender. I have only had ribs THAT tender once in my life and thus I judge all other experiences to that one instance. The verdict here? The rub is off the charts flavorful, with equal balance in heat, sweet, salt, tang, and spice. You could eat it without any sauce and it would still be good. Had the chicken wings and pork spare ribs. Both were flavorful. Tenderness rating though? Not as high as I would have preferred. As for the sides, the Mac and cheese is it! Order two! The green beans are spicy so beware.

Federalist Pig is located in Adams Morgan off of the main strip and in a somewhat non-descript, industrial metal storefront. You just might walk past it without noticing it, but here’s why you should make it a point to stop in and eat here – they make great BBQ. There is an outdoor seating area, which is highly recommended for those nice weather days. But, if you want to take in the whole experience and atmosphere, eat inside (be forewarned, you will most likely smell of BBQ until you shower and wash your clothes). Step inside the metal-faced BBQ shack and you’ll find seating for approximately 25 people, funny BBQ-inspired drawings on the wall, and laughter and smiles abound. During popular times, you will find it hard to get a table or a seat on the bench that runs the length of the restaurant. And if you do, you will probably be cozying up to your neighbor(s)! The bustling kitchen is situated along one side of the space and open to the restaurant. A short wall separates the line to order BBQ from the kitchen, so while you wait, you will have the opportunity to take in the sights, smells, heat, and conversation of the kitchen. There are a few small fridges that have craft brews and sodas ready for your choosing. The staff members are very friendly, helping to create a warm and welcoming vibe.  After you order, they will call your name and you can grab your tray of BBQ. You’ll find lots of different BBQ sauces to try (sticky garlic, anyone?). Try a little of the BBQ without any sauces first so you can appreciate the taste. I’ve tried all of their BBQ meats and have been thoroughly impressed with the quality and consistency of flavor and taste. Their sides, like the brussels sprouts and mac and cheese, are great complements to the BBQ meats, but are on the small side. The Texas toast and pickles are great, little additions full of flavor. Don’t kid yourself into thinking this a healthy dining option – it’s terrible for you, but such a nice treat for your taste buds. Note that there are few options for vegetarians, and they are closed Monday and Tuesday. The food is a little more expensive and the portions are a little smaller than its competitors, but the quality is a cut above. It gets loud and crowded, so it might not be the best choice for a romantic, quiet first date. Instead, bring a friend or two, and get messy while you dig into some of DC’s best BBQ. After you experience dining inside the restaurant once, I would recommend sitting outside (when possible) or ordering pickup. Get there early, because they do run out of BBQ meats!

Staff was outside handing out menus. They were extremely nice and very helpful. The smell of bbq was around but not super strong, that’s ok though. The seating was extremely scarce because they just don’t have much there. Ok, now to the food. Ordering was easy. I got the ribs, cheddar jalapeño sausage, brisket, and pork shoulder with red potato salad, green beans, Mac and cheese, and fries. Every meal comes with butter garlic toast which is great. The ribs were great. Spare ribs done right with a great seasoning on it. Cheddar jalapeño sausage was good, it has good snap but I was hoping for more of a variety of sausage. Pork shoulder was good, tender, and well seasoned. The brisket was left for something to be desired. It was pretty bland and tough. Green beans were ok, they had good flavor but were just a little too spicy to really enjoy. The potato salad could have been better if the potatoes were broken down more. They were large pieces that allowed for the potatoes to hijack the flavor. Mac and cheese and the fries were average. I’m rating it 4 stars solely based on ribs and staff.  No fifth star because they did not have baked beans, that is absolute must for a bbq joint. No fifth star because the food did not warrant five stars. Recommend getting a rack of ribs and sharing or if alone, just grab a half rack and be done with it.
The beat shoulder i have tried. Service is great

On our trip to DC we had the pulled pork, pork belly, smoked turkey, and brisket. All meat was very mosit and tender. Green beans and smoked cheddar mac and cheese hit the spot as well. I would highly recommend this place.
Great bbq pulled pork and turkey were delicious great service
Best barbecue in DC.

This was an absolute disaster. We ordered from a very limited menu due to the service running out of food. We then sat down outside and tried to begin eating but were asked to leave. The reason seemed that we had ordered take-home. We decided to eat at the restaurant instead. Were were then harassed and asked to leave even though there was plenty of empty seating around us. This is an absolute disaster and a shame to DC, were most restaurants are more than happy to accommodate. I will never be eating here again. You should be ashamed of yourself. The food was burned and greasy.

However, the short rib (Thursdays only) was overrated, and the menu is very heavily pork focused, so despite the large number of items on the menu, it was actually not quite as comprehensive as hoped. OTOH, maybe their focus is a good thing?  And the “may be the best in the city” isn’t the praise it sounds like, because their competition is almost universally terrible.

Forget, Hill country BBQ. This is the spot for amazing BBQ. The pork rib tips are cooked to perfection, taste and juiciness. The ribs come of the bone with ease and the dry rub is really all you need to enjoy them. Though there's plenty of sauces to use. The sticky garlic was my favorite. The pork shoulder was a great combination of fat and meat for the perfect taste. The pork belly was to die for and the dish that stole the show. Let me be clear none of the meats require sauce they are all tasteful and juicy. The dinning room is communal setting of wood tables and stools. Perfect for a BBQ joint.

Federalist Pig serves up tasty barbecue with a wide range of homemade sauces. The sandwich menu is creative, and the platters offer a chance to try a few options. Would give it five stars if not for the cleanliness. Sat at a back bar by the bathrooms with generations of barbecue sauce caked on the wall and adjacent refrigerator. Some of the barbecue bottles were crusted shut despite the place having opened within the hour. Child seats were stacked inside one of the bathrooms. This is a high-traffic place (and justifiably popular because of the food) that perhaps has just outgrown its tiny digs.

Awesome BBQ !! Everything there was delicious, the bbq and sides. The inside of the restaurant is not that big, the place was clean and the service was good.

Went on a random Wednesday night after a drink at the Line with some buddies for the first time. Missed out on Brisket and any kind of ribs because we arrived at 8:20PM (skip the before-dinner-drink and don't be late)! Had the pork shoulder, pork belly, chicken wings and jalepeno cheddar sausage, with mac n cheese, brussel sprouts and slaw on the side. The shoulder was top-tier flavorful without being smothered in sauce upon delivery, high marks. The wings were excellent as was the pork belly. The sausage was phenomenal, I was surprised to find it well balanced and not just a jumble of indistinct intensity. Went back the next night for the brisket - insanely good. I was very pleased overall and wager you won't be disappointed if you visit.

I grew up in Texas and lived briefly in the Hill Country where some of the BEST Bbq, not only Texas, but in the entire country is located. I recently moved to DC and was looking for a taste of home. I was very excited to see that Texas Monthly sang their praises of this place and said it competes with anything Texas has to offer. I also knew even before stepping inside it was going to be great when I spotted a sign saying that they close when the food runs out. I tried their brisket, pork belly, pork ribs, and mac and cheese. The brisket was moist, flavorful, and had the right amount of smokiness.  The pork belly was tender and melted in my mouth. The mac and cheese tasted like it was made at home and gone too quickly. The only complaint was that the pork ribs were dry and a little tough. Nonetheless, I have found a good replacement for great Bbq in the DMV and will be coming back.

Finally, one of the other employees let me try a pork rib as they were finishing up which was 1-tasty and 2-really nice of them. I’ve been to BBQ places all over Texas, and this place was as good or better. The brisket was incredible. Very fatty, but so tender. They have a few different BBQ sauces and they’re all different and very tasty. It’s also a pretty good value. I’d travel all the way across town to eat here again.

OK, so I really love this place and try to come here at least once a week, or once every few weeks.  The food is fantastic and the menu is always changing. The last time I came in, I ordered the fixer, which is pulled pork, pimento cheese, pork rinds, onions on a potato bun.  I really liked this sandwich and I don't really consider myself a big sandwich person either.  My favorite item on their menu is not really barbecue but the brussel sprouts. I kid you not when I say these are the greatest brussel sprouts to ever grace this good planet. They are crispy, cooked perfectly and they give you a gigantic AF portion every time for a fantastic price.  I tell everyone about this place. Good lord this was good. The ribs were my favorite, the pulled pork was a close second. The brisket was a little dry. The mac and cheese was the showstopper, the sauces were decent, the baked beans were disappointing. Overall, FP was amazing.

The barbecue here is fantastic! The building is a little cramped but the atmosphere is fun and pleasant. The rib tips might have been the best I've ever had. Skip the sauce and just enjoy the flavorful smoked meats. The pork belly was good and the brisket was melt-in-your-mouth perfection. Skip the jalapeno cheddar sausage.  The 'plate for 2' was enough food for my family of three, with a little left over!  I'm a Brussels sprouts fan, and their crispy Brussels sprouts were fantastic, skip the fries and go straight for these as your side. It was very relaxed and the service was efficient. The guy who owns the joint was working the cash register and he was a normal guy who was happy to have guests at his eatery, super cool. 10/10 would fly back to DC to eat lunch here again.

One of the better tasting BBQ places in the area. I would have given it 5 stars if they had any service at all!? There was a lot of confusion about if customers needed to pick the food up once it was done vs our "server" bring it to us. We had to shout our order to the cashier. NOT all three items they offer are on the gross dirty paper menus. They're on a board behind you as you stands facing the cashier?! The cashier gave us SOME of our drinks, took our name, & then we had a random employee walk us to our table. He never showed back up. I wondered in to find out what was going on with our order and the strangers sat at our same table... After we had been sat & waited several moments. I received our food after I went inside to ask what was taking so long or see if it got marked as a take out. The guy manning the grill asked if I heard him shout for us. I said nope, never had a restaurant shout for customers that were sat at a table. I had to ask for the rest of our drinks and make 4 trips. The random employee stood there as I juggled hot metal pans?! I had to go back inside to get sauces, napkins, silverware, etc. from the very back next to a sink/employee area. The cashier told me to go back there. After everything was said and done. I carried everything back inside because they don't have a trashcan outside. I'm assuming it's not a self serve place from all the confusion happening outside. They don't have signs stating they're self serve but you'd have to visit more than once to even know menu is half written on papper & the other half on the wall behind you. The food was delicious but the service, organization (lack of), & poor layout left a lot to be desired. Place a to go order and don't wreck your BBQ experience.
tasty and very heavy sandwiches, fast service, not many vegan friendly options, they're missing out
Hands down,  the best bbq in Adam's morgan,  if not all of DC
Great pulled pork and brisket. Their potato salad is pretty good. Ribs could be good depending on the day.

When I first moved to DC and learned that Rocklands passed for acceptable BBQ, I was very worried. Federalist Pig restored my faith in DC BBQ. I personally recommend the sandwiches, though I've enjoyed most everything I've gotten on the menu.

Best BBQ in DC bar none !!! Today was Father's Day 2018. The place was so popular that they were completely sold out of brisket, ribs and chicken before 6pm. However, they still had plenty of goodies such as pork bellies and sausages, along with all the sides. Their smoked ham and pulled pork sandwiches are awesome too. Generous portions and fantastic sauces. Everything was on the spicy side, so sensitive palates and stomachs take heed. These people definitely know BBQ!!!

Love this place and the kitchen team! The food is just so good and it always taste better with each visit. My favorite is the pork belly. I recommend getting the sampler so you can try the different meats they serve. If you're not into spicy side dishes, don't go for the Chipotle green beans side.

We came here to eat while on vacation. Was disappointed that there is very little seating. I got a BBQ pork sandwich to split with my son. He couldn’t eat it as all the BBQ sauce is very spicy. I would at least recommend making a sweet sauce for the littles. The Mac and cheese was the best I’ve ever had! The people who work there are super friendly! One made  us two grilled cheese on the house for my boys without us even asking or complaining. That’s how attentive they are! Giving a 4 star just because I think you should add a sweet sauce.
Sooo GOOD!
Excellent food, didnt make me regret being Vegetarian because they had a meatless option! Woohoo BBQ!
Absolutely the BEST BBQ in DC!!! Tip- Try to get there between 5pm and 7ish it seems like after that is when they start to sell out.
The Turkey breast and ribs are a must.
Oh, wow.  BBQ pork sandwich, fries, sauces, all AMAZING!  Not cheap, but well worth it!
Good BBQ. Won't change your life but some of the best BBQ in DC.

Won't sell by the quarter pound, only the half pound, unlike every other decent BBQ joint in the DC area. Their food is fine, but that sort of inflexibility isn't worth nothing with in a city with so many options.

Great food , will definitely return
Excellent all around! On par with or better than Fox Bros Atlanta. Prices are also more than fair
Love this place. Highly recommend the brisket, spare ribs, and crispy brussels sprouts.  Pictured:   the wild thing sandwich, from the special menu.
Excellent BBQ!
Very nice and chill neighborhood BBQ place. You can have some delicious meat with a beer and watch soccer on TV. They also have a small outdoor seating area, perfect for enjoying the nice weather.
I'm a southern BBQ snob and proud of it, but this place nailed it. Not a big fan of the smoked sausage, but the brisket and pork were awesome.
WOW, such a great vibe supported by a great staff and menu. Oversized picnic tables out front add to the fun!
Fantastic food and amazing staff. HIGHLY recommend!
The word perfection doesn't do justice to each item on the menu. The brisket brings joy to my tongue, stomach, heart, and soul.
Hands down best BBQ joint in the area. Ribs are on point, and the brisket has flavor for each bite. Brussel sprouts, sausage, cole slaw, all excellent.
The smoke cauliflower sandwich was amazing--so nice to be able to eat an entree at a bbq place as a vegetarian!

Had to throw up about an hour after eating there, possibly due to dangerously undercooked baked beans.  Brisket was lacking in flavor.
